Zimbabwe army commander Lieutenant General Edzayi Chimonyo dies in hospital. [Courtesy]  Zimbabwe's army commander died early on Thursday after succumbing to cancer, the presidential spokesman said.  The army holds an outsized influence in Zimbabwean politics. In November 2017, the army stepped in to oust the late Robert Mugabe and pave way for incumbent President Emmerson Mnangagwa.  Lieutenant General Edzayi Chimonyo, who was appointed to the position after the coup, had been battling cancer, George Charamba, the presidential spokesman wrote on Twitter.  Chimonyo, like all the current crop of military generals in Zimbabwe, is a former fighter in the country's 1970s war of independence.  Hospice improves quality of life for cancer patients in great pain  My 30-year battle with colon cancer  Men shun vasectomy despite the procedure being ‘safe and cheap’  CNN anchor discloses her battle with ovarian cancer on TV The opposition often accuse the army of openly siding with the ruling party in violation of the constitution.   Fate of Cancer patients   KTN Morning Express 5th February 2016, Kenyatta Hospital joins the Fight against Cancer  Cancer scourge:Reports show that cancer causes 27,000 deaths in Kenya By  Josphat Thiong’o  | 2 hours ago By Reuters | 19 hours ago By Xinhua | 19 hours ago By Patrick Vidija | 1 day ago